Answer:
"In mathematics we never understand; we only get used to."

-John von Neumann
The above statement is so right that Mathematics is the ultimate tool of our intelligence.
So much so that in 20th century science the word "mathematics" was used more often than "physics" and "chemistry" taken together! Many great mathematicians have won Nobel awards and also many physicists have taken their researches to Mathematics from Physics.



"The most beautiful and profound things we can experience is the mystery. Knowledge leaves in us darkness."

- Albert Einstein

Mystery is an inherent feature of Maths. We know the answer but what is the concept or reason behind that answer is a mystery to us! Many concepts in Maths have never been explained (at least explained in an acceptable form).
For example, we know that $\sqrt{2} $ is a irrational number of the form p/q where p and q are two different numbers. Similarly we know other irrational numbers like 'pi', 'e' and even 'e^(pi i ) + 1' for those who know Complex numbers.
In a similar way there are many concepts in Maths that have no explanation - e.g. the concept of Infinity.
We know that there are Infinite Natural numbers (1, 2, 3, 4...). When all of them are written down using different types of digits (even from the first chapter of the book to the last chapter). When each of these digit runs out of the available 10 types of digits. The next digit used is the first non duplicate digit (those available are unique). If we don't get any digit then we add some zeros to the end so that the result is still a natural number. We don't know what would happen next.
We just know that there are Infinity Infinite Natural numbers.

We see that many things in nature like Infinity, Pi, e... and even certain laws of Physics are just a beautiful fact of Nature. No explanation is provided for those. In Mathematics also there are many things which are just known without any rational explanation or even without any proof.
